	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=4&mid=102920548132310>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=102920548132310>RE: Damage Cap</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=102920548132310#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Aug 12th 10:36 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=124788><span id=Scholar>Heidii</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>36 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The damage cap for under 20 caps all weapons at maximum 14 dmg weapons....so an 8 dmg weapon was not actually being &quot;capped&quot; as such under 20, that's why you saw no difference. And strength of 105 won't add much of a strength bonus to your damage output either. As your weapon skill rises in the next few levels you'll get a small increase in damage, but not much off such a low damage weapon. Until you get to level 28 the only increases in damage come from strength and weapon skill increases, and these act like a percentage modifier which is rounded down after being applied...so a 10% increase on a 8 dmg weapon would be 0.8 rounded down to zero...whereas a 10% increase on a 12dmg weapon would be 1.2 rounded down to 1. If you really want to hit harder straight away you're going to have to get a higher damage weapon. Get yourself a Centi short sword for 200-300pp 12/25 and you'll be hitting for 25 at the same speed as the fiber.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Aug 13 09:27:56 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
